The data is collected by New York City Taxi and Limousine commission (popularly known as TLC) about Green Taxis. The data used for this challenge is the trips made for September 2015. This dataset can be directly downloaded from the site http://www.nyc.gov/html/tlc/html/about/trip_record_data.shtml

Function to load the necessary libraries

load_package <- function(packages){ 
  new_package <- packages[!(packages %in% installed.packages()[, "Package"])]   
  if (length(new_package))  
    install.packages(new_package, dependencies = TRUE)  
  sapply(packages, require, character.only = TRUE)  
}   

packages <- c("ggplot2", "lars","knitr", "dplyr", "randomForest","gplots", "corrplot","caret","RCurl","data.table", "rattle","rmarkdown", "lubridate", "ggmap", "tidyverse", "GGally", "olsrr") 
              
load_package(packages) # Calling the load_package function

Question 2

1. Plot a histogram of the number of the trip distance (“Trip Distance”).

Histogram is a plot which is used to visualize the frequency distribution of the continous data. Histograms are considered to be a good summary for the distribution of values in a large dataset.

ggplot(data=green_taxi, aes(green_taxi$Trip_distance)) + geom_histogram(bins = 100) +
  xlab("Trip Distance traveled (miles)") + ggtitle("Histogram of Trip distance")

Trip Distance is measured in miles. Since majority of the trips are taken for less than 20 miles, the normal histogram plot does not provide any useful information.

ggplot(data=green_taxi, aes(log(green_taxi$Trip_distance))) + geom_histogram(bins = 100) + xlab("log of Trip Distance traveled (miles)") + ggtitle("Log-Scaled Histogram of Trip distance")

Log-scaled histogram is used to make the histogram more readable.

2. Report any structure you find and any hypotheses you have about that structure.

Since the histogram is heavily skewed, after some trials to find the plot that better describes the pattern, the trip distance of 20 miles seems to be a better number to zoom the histogram.

ggplot(data=green_taxi[green_taxi$Trip_distance < 20,], aes(Trip_distance)) + geom_histogram(bins = 50) + xlab("Trip Distance traveled (miles)") + ggtitle("Enlarged Histogram of Trip distance from 0 to 20 miles")

Structure - The plot is left skewed showing that there are more trips taken for a shorted distance when compared to longer trips.

Hypotheses - We can infer from the histogram that people in NYC prefer to take green taxi for shorter trips within 5 miles rather than traveling to other cities or traveling for a long distance. There are very less trips which was taken for longer distance, it may be the tourist who might have toured around the city.

2. We’d like to get a rough sense of identifying trips that originate or terminate at one of the NYC area airports. Can you provide a count of how many transactions fit this criteria, the average fare, and any other interesting characteristics of these trips.

There are 3 airports in New York City.

  1. JFK (John F. Kennedy International Airport)
  2. LGA (LaGaurdia Airport)
  3. EWR (Newark Liberty International Airport)

JFK and EWR has special rates in the RateCodeID. JFK ratecode id is 2 and EWR ID is 3. We can get the latitude and longitude of any address using a ggmap function called “geocode”.

#get latitude and longitude of LaGaurdia airport
laGaurdia <- geocode('Queens, NY 11371')
laGaurdia
##         lon      lat
## 1 -73.87425 40.77664

The pickup or dropoff location will not be exactly at the airport’s latitude and longitude. Hence it is better to round the latitude and longitude to 4 decimal places.

#rounding latitude and longitude to 4 decimal places
laGaurdia$lon = round(laGaurdia$lon, 4)
laGaurdia$lat = round(laGaurdia$lat, 4)

#get latitude and longitude of trips upto 4 decimal places
green_taxi$pickup_long <- as.numeric(substring(green_taxi$Pickup_longitude, 1, 8))
green_taxi$pickup_lat <- as.numeric(substring(green_taxi$Pickup_latitude, 1, 8))
green_taxi$dropoff_long <- as.numeric(substring(green_taxi$Dropoff_longitude, 1, 8))
green_taxi$dropoff_lat <- as.numeric(substring(green_taxi$Dropoff_latitude, 1, 8))

#Retrieve all the records which satisfies the airport condition
airport_taxi = green_taxi[(green_taxi$RateCodeID == 2) | (green_taxi$RateCodeID == 3) | (((green_taxi$pickup_lat) == laGaurdia$lat) & ((green_taxi$pickup_long) == laGaurdia$lon)) | (((green_taxi$dropoff_lat) == laGaurdia$lat) & ((green_taxi$dropoff_long) == laGaurdia$lon)),]
paste0("Total number of pickup and dropoff trips to and from the airport: ", nrow(airport_taxi))
## [1] "Total number of pickup and dropoff trips to and from the airport: 5552"
#print average fare, tip, toll and total amount
avg_amount <- tribble(~Fare_Amount, ~Tip_Amount, ~Toll_Amount, ~Total_Amount,
        paste0("$",round(mean(airport_taxi$Fare_amount),3)), paste0("$",round(mean(airport_taxi$Tip_amount),3)),
        paste0("$",round(mean(airport_taxi$Tolls_amount),3)), paste0("$",round(mean(airport_taxi$Total_amount),3)))
kable(avg_amount)

There are 5552 trips to the airport. LaGaurdia airport has no pickup or dropoff records from the data. Maybe there is no route access for Green taxi to LaGaurdia airport.

The average Fare for the airport is $48.97.

Other interesting factors:

  1. There are negative fares recorded and all the negative fares use VendorID = 2 which is VeriFone.Inc.

  2. Around 79% of the total trips to airports is to JFK airport. Probably JFK airport is more busy than Newark airport.

  3. However, it is only 0.3% trips are for airport when compared to non airport trips. Hence whenever a trip is for airport, it is 79% chance that the airport is JFK. However, very less people prefer traveling to airports using Green taxi.

Handling missing data

There are two columns which has missing values.

Ehail_fee - Completely missing

Trip_type - 4 missing values

All the 4 trip_type has RateCodeID as “99” which is not an actual rate code provided by TLC. These missing values can be handled in the following way.

  1. Remove the entire row which contains a missing value.

  2. Impute the missing values with most occuring value in the column which is 1.

  3. Impute the missing values using KNN Imputation.

For now we will impute the missing values with the most common occuring value 1.

#Remove the entire column
green_taxi$Ehail_fee <- NULL

#Cited mode function from Stackoverflow https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2547402/is-there-a-built-in-function-for-finding-the-mode
Mode <- function(x) {
  ux <- unique(x)
  ux[which.max(tabulate(match(x, ux)))]
}

green_taxi$Trip_type[is.na(green_taxi$Trip_type)] <- Mode(green_taxi$Trip_type)

Adding Tip percentage column/variable

Tip percentage is calculated by tip amount divided by the total amount.

#filter the data with total amount greater than 0 and calculate tip percent
green_taxi <- green_taxi[green_taxi$Total_amount > 0,]
green_taxi$Tip_percent <- (green_taxi$Tip_amount/green_taxi$Total_amount)*100

Stratified sampling to split our data into training and test sets

We will split the dataset into train and test data with 80:20 ratio for train and test. The train data is used to build a regression model so that the model can learn any pattern with 80% of the data. Inorder to validate them, we use test data to predict the tip percent by hiding the response variable and comparing the predictions with the actual value using r squared and Root mean square error evaluation metric.

targetVar <- "Tip_percent"
Xvars <- c('VendorID', 'Store_and_fwd_flag', 'RateCodeID', 'Pickup_longitude',
       'Pickup_latitude', 'Dropoff_longitude', 'Dropoff_latitude',
       'Passenger_count', 'Trip_distance', 'Fare_amount', 'Extra', 'MTA_tax',
       'Tip_amount', 'Tolls_amount', 'improvement_surcharge',
       'Total_amount', 'Payment_type', 'Trip_type')
set.seed(3456)
inTrain <- createDataPartition(y = green_taxi[,targetVar], list = FALSE, p = .80)
train <- green_taxi[inTrain,]
test <- green_taxi[-inTrain,]
stopifnot(nrow(train) + nrow(test) == nrow(green_taxi))

Function to create a model formula

createModelFormula <- function(targetVar, xVars, includeIntercept = TRUE){
  if(includeIntercept){
    modelForm <- as.formula(paste(targetVar, "~", paste(xVars, collapse = '+ ')))
  } else {
    modelForm <- as.formula(paste(targetVar, "~", paste(xVars, collapse = '+ '), -1))
  }
  return(modelForm)
}
set.seed(13)
#Input the independent variable and response variable to get the formula
full_modelForm <- createModelFormula(targetVar, Xvars)

Feature selection using Backward Elimination

Backward elimination has an advantage over Forward selection as Forward selection is a greedy approach. It is possible for the variables to have predictive power even though some of the subset of the variables do not explain and Forward selection will not catch this. Hence, Backward elimination is useful as it starts with all the variables and any correlation and joint prediction can be found easily.

Model selection - Final Thoughts

The full model of multiple regression and selected model from backward elimination is almost equal. As a final model, I would prefer the selected model as it gives the same prediction with fewer features which makes the model less complicated.

Question 5 - Option A: Distributions

1. Build a derived variable representing the average speed over the course of a trip.

We know that speed = distance/time. We can derive the average speed over the course of the trip by getting the trip distance and calculating time taken from pickup and dropoff columns.

#filter data with distance greater than 0.
trip_data = green_taxi[green_taxi$Trip_distance > 0,]

#Extract time in seconds
trip_data$Time = as.numeric(difftime(trip_data$Lpep_dropoff_datetime, trip_data$lpep_pickup_datetime, units = "secs"))

#Create a new variable for average speed
trip_data$Avg_speed = round((trip_data$Trip_distance)/round(((trip_data$Time)/3600),2),2)

#remove records with average speed equals infinity
trip_data = trip_data[trip_data$Avg_speed != Inf,] #Remove Inf records

summary(trip_data$Avg_speed) #overview of the column
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    0.00    9.42   11.82   13.30   15.10 7670.00
hist(trip_data$Avg_speed[trip_data$Avg_speed < 15], main = "Average speed distribution", xlab = "Average Speed (miles)")

2. Can you perform a test to determine if the average trip speeds are materially the same in all weeks of September? If you decide they are not the same, can you form a hypothesis regarding why they differ?

Let us define the hypothesis as below,

  • Null hypothesis H0 : The means of the speeds for all the weeks are same.
  • Alternate Hypothesis H1 : Atleast one of the mean speed is not equal.
trip_data$week = as.numeric(strftime(trip_data$lpep_pickup_datetime, "%W"))
avg_summary = trip_data[,c('week', 'Avg_speed')] %>%  group_by(week_number = week) %>% summarise(Average_Speed = mean(Avg_speed))
kable(avg_summary)
week_number Average_Speed
35 13.87414
36 13.06888
37 12.99208
38 13.56968
39 12.81951

We will implement this statistically using one way ANOVA to compare the means of the speed for all the 5 weeks.

boxplot(Avg_speed ~ week, main = "boxplot of Average speed grouped by week", xlab='week',ylab='Avg speed', data = trip_data[trip_data$Avg_speed < 20,])

anova1 = aov(Avg_speed ~ week, data = trip_data) #Fitting ANOVA 
summary(anova1) #Prints the summary and ANOVA table
##                  Df    Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)    
## week              1     36057   36057   86.31 <2e-16 ***
## Residuals   1464585 611827514     418                   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
#function to plot the means with 95% confidence interval
plotmeans(Avg_speed ~ week, data = trip_data, main = "Average speed grouped by week with 95% confidence interval")
## Warning in arrows(x, li, x, pmax(y - gap, li), col = barcol, lwd = lwd, :
## zero-length arrow is of indeterminate angle and so skipped
## Warning in arrows(x, ui, x, pmin(y + gap, ui), col = barcol, lwd = lwd, :
## zero-length arrow is of indeterminate angle and so skipped

From the summary of the anova, the p value is less than 0.001 which is highly significant. Hence we reject the null hypothesis and conclude that atleast one of the mean speed for the weeks are not equal.

Can you build up a hypothesis of average trip speed as a function of time of day?

Let us define the hypothesis as below,

  • Null hypothesis H0 : The means of the speeds for the hours is the same.

trip_data$hour = as.numeric(strftime(trip_data$lpep_pickup_datetime, "%H"))

time_summary = trip_data[,c('hour', 'Avg_speed')] %>%  group_by(Hours = hour) %>% summarise(Average_Speed = mean(Avg_speed))
